        <bioghist id="ref10">
            <head>Biographical Note</head>
            <chronlist>
                <chronitem>
                    <date>1881</date>
                    <event>Born in Russia</event>
                </chronitem>
                <chronitem>
                    <date>1899</date>
                    <event>Joined the Russian Imperial Army</event>
                </chronitem>
                <chronitem>
                    <date>1901-1904</date>
                    <event>Road and topographical surveying in Manchuria (Northeast China) for Russian military</event>
                </chronitem>
                <chronitem>
                    <date>1904</date>
                    <event>Fought in Russo-Japanese War</event>
                </chronitem>
                <chronitem>
                    <date>1907-1912</date>
                    <event>Road and topographical surveying in Japan</event>
                </chronitem>
                <chronitem>
                    <date>1914-1916</date>
                    <event>Fought in World War I as an aviation officer and promoted to Colonel in the 8th Siberian Mountain Artillery of the Russian Imperial Army. Decorated with St. George's Military Cross</event>
                </chronitem>
                <chronitem>
                    <date>1918</date>
                    <event>Applied through the United States Embassy in Japan for permission to join the American Expeditionary Forces (AEF)</event>
                </chronitem>
                <chronitem>
                    <date>1920</date>
                    <event>Immigrated to the United States</event>
                </chronitem>
                <chronitem>
                    <date>1922-1928</date>
                    <event>Map draftsman for Rand McNally &amp; Co. and South American division of the American Geographical Society</event>
                </chronitem>
                <chronitem>
                    <date>1928</date>
                    <event>Died in New York City, NY</event>
                </chronitem>
            </chronlist>
        </bioghist>
        <scopecontent id="ref12">
            <head>Scope and Content of Collection</head>
            <p>This collection documents the military career of Mikhail Mikhailovich Kostenko during the Russo-Japanese War and World War I, as well as his post-war immigration to the United States. The collection includes family documents, military records, correspondence, photographs, and memorabilia.</p>
            <p>The 
                <emph render="bold">Biographical File</emph> relates mainly to Kostenko's life in the United States, and includes identification documents, naturalization records, and family records. In particular, there is collected correspondence and genealogical information gathered by Kostenko's son, Barry (Boris) Kostenko.</p>
            <p>The 
                <emph render="bold">Military Career File</emph> relates to Kostenko’s military career and Russian military operations, especially in Japan between 1904 and 1920, and consists of reports, orders, certificates, sketches, and maps.</p>
            <p>The 
                <emph render="bold">Photographs</emph> are mostly from Kostenko's time spent stationed in Japan, and 
                <emph render="bold">Memorabilia</emph> consists of medals, badges, ribbons, military adornments, and map draftsman tools.</p>
        </scopecontent>
